Something is bugging me about the examples he&#x27;s using there, I&#x27;ve never seen singletons used that way. these are just static initializers.<p><pre><code>  testCreditCardCharge() {
	  CreditCardProcessor.init();
	  CreditCard c =  new CreditCard(
	    &quot;1234 5678 9012 3456&quot;, 5, 2008);
	  c.charge(100);
	}
</code></pre>
Instead I would expect a singleton to be used this way. Which takes care of initialization where its needed.<p><pre><code>		class CreditCard {
			private number;
			function charge(amount){
				processor = CreditCardProcessor.getInstance();
				processor.go(number, amount);
			}
		}
</code></pre>
I&#x27;m not saying this is better way to process this datamodel, but it is the correct way to use a singleton.
